Vincents @ Cafe Du Pays has impressed and innovated in response to COVID. The shrimp and salmon were a huge success at our home, paired with the delicata squash and a fresh baguette. The 'make at home' kits are of high quality and make it easy to please anyone in your family.
Good prices and quality of ingredients is high.

I have to admit I'm a bit picky regarding French restaurants; but Cafe du Pays is very good, the food and even more the drinks. The menu is not a lot of fun and it could have more original items (reason for the 4 stars)

I'm love this themed restaurant, and servers are all dressed up. They have a lot of interesting and good classic drinks. Their food is small plates, and they are meant to be shared. We loved their Cuban Cigars, Brie, Bacon Bites, and Deep Fried Tomatoes.I highly recommend this place!
The food was excellent. We had the duck and the monkfish. Portions were tasty but not generous.
Great food!
Great food. Great staff.

Amazing dining experience! Cozy atmosphere with a great decor, and thoughtful, attentive service. The menu is mainly Québécois classics revisited. But wow do they do a great job! The dishes are simple, no frills,  but incredibly delicious. The sugar pie is literally the best I have ever had in my life (and I've had A LOT of them). Cocktails are super good too. Really worth it.
Delicious Quebecois food, good wine advice.  Compact menu of appetizers, small plates, and main dishes.
Foodie place with good French press coffee.
Nice cozy restaurant with amazing food. Every dish was delicious! We had drinks with apps and snacks.

There are a lot of restaurants in Boston, however none come with the same atmosphere and experience that Cafe du Pays has to offer. You hear the term "feel at home" a lot, but it's not until dining at Cafe du Pays that I felt the that term fully realized. With an exceptional staff and a beautiful, warm, and welcoming environment, Cafe du Pays serves some of the most delicious, authentic, and satisfying food this city has to offer. The drinks are also top notch. This is the perfect place to have a memorable dining experience, whether it be a date night, dinner with friends, or just reading a book at the bar with a cocktail and a cheese plate, Cafe du Pays delivers a dining experience from start to finish that will leave you smiling for days!

We made reservations at Cafe du Pays for New Years Eve and I'm glad we did. We were welcomed into the restaurant and shown to a high top upstairs. The restaurant is charming and feels welcoming. Our waitress was soft-spoken, friendly, and helped make our evening enjoyable.  We ordered a half dozen oysters, sourdough bread, foie gras, smoked head cheese, and poutine to start.  I didn't partake in the poutine but my cousin loved it. The oysters were slightly briny and shucked perfectly. We also loved the large portion of horseradish. The sourdough, foie gras, and headcheese were all enjoyable but we didn't taste much of the smoke flavor on the headcheese.  For entrees, we ordered the swordfish, ham, and the half duck. My half duck was definitely too much for one person but I didn't mind because it was delicious!! The duck was perfectly cooked, and the roasted garlic was delicious. My husband loved the ham dish and was pleasantly surprised that it wasn't too salty. My cousin tried swordfish for the first time and thanks to the preparation loved it.  For dessert my husband ordered the sugar pie, and my cousin ordered the special of the night. I did take a Lactaid pill and try a bite and they were delicious!

Beautiful food and drinks. Stylishly done French Canadian comfort food with a smart, compact menu so you can almost order one of everything. The gravy on the poutine is nice and meaty. Wine list and cocktails are perfect. Highly recommended.
As a Canadian I have to admit they made an effort. But it does not taste authentic. GOOD, but not like the real thing.

The charcuterie was a steal at $6 and the complexity of the seasoning in the dish was outstanding. The mustard was to die for - very sharp.For wine we sipped on a bottle from Vermont! The sommelier provided a great overview of the wine after listening to our preferences. The Iapetus red from Vermont was tannic, full bodied and quite spectacular.
Quant place, good food, portion sized so that you can enjoy 3 or 3 courses which I like. V good cheeses and charcuterie
Excellent food, both creative combinations (tempura dill fronds on a beet salad) and staples like Steak Au Poivre. Service was friendly and the atmosphere perfect for our double date.
A a real find. The food and service were top-notch .

Great restaurant.  Had the best Duck I have ever had.  Really nice ambiance.   Highly recommend it as a date night.   Will definitely be going back.   Besides the duck I highly recomend the meat pie for an appetizer.
No  wheelchair access in the store! Food is great, perfect wines, cool atmosphere
I wanted to love this place, and while its great for a date night, the waiters are a bit temperamental, and the food really is just average.
Good food but very small portions and expensive. It's only a good place to impress your date...

Great French (Canadian) cuisine. Good authentic poutine app, but that was the boring part - everything we tried was delicious. Fantastic service and advice. Note it can get a bit noisy with groups in here, but we had no troubles carrying on a conversation.

Excellent spot for dinner.  I'd probably do 4.5 stars if it was an option. I liked the atmosphere and the service was good. The food was just okay, though, and when you factor in the price, I wouldn't go back. I got the poutine and a dish called Chou Farci, which contained mushrooms and carrot tahini, as well as lentils, I think.
Their poutine was $10 and came in a tiny paper box, with sad looking balls of cheese. Needless to say, was not a great experience.

Excellent food! Everything from the sourdough bread to the desserts was fantastic. The service was outstanding. Very friendly, helpful and knowledgeable waitstaff. Food isn't very expensive and more than worth it.

Look at how happy of a birthday boy I am from eating at Cafe du Pays.  I loved eating here. Take a look at the first photo. That's their duck dish. Are you seeing what I'm seeing. An absolutely gorgeous piece of seared duck where the meat is oh so tender, the fat cuts like butter and the skin gives it a nice crispy touch.  The second picture is the Chou-Farci which is their staple stuffed cabbage vegetable dish. Their was so much complexity in this dish with the tahini and the layers of mushrooms.  Step outside your comfort zone and have a glass of cognac for dessert.

The food was very good, the atmosphere and venue, not so much. It is two levels. We sat on the first level, where the tables are in advance of the hostess station, so as you eat the hostess is standing right over you. As are the often confused diners that enter the restaurant. Up a few steps is the second level where the bathrooms are located. Be careful it's dark. Really dark. And if you or one of your crew are in a wheelchair, you are SOL at this place. Very limited bar. Very pretentious vibe. Café enjoys many great reviews and ratings, but I just didn't get it. Felt like there was a secret club and I was not a member. I know of what I speak, and I am not a hater. Read my many restaurant reviews.

Cozy atmosphere and hospitable servers who know the menu and wine selection well. The mushroom chips, sourdough bread and pickled radishes are so memorable, my favorites among all orders. Fresh fish (catch of the day: flounder) is tender with flavorful crispy skin.  The restaurant serves unique Canadian French fusion cuisine. Bravos to chefs for their adventuris menu design. It was fine, but over-priced. We ordered the cheese plate ($15) and it only came with two pieces of bread, we had to pay more for more bread. I would rather a place factor in the cost of bread and just bring it to the table freely rather than feel nickel-and-dimed. None of the dishes were remarkable, probably wouldn't return, but other than feeling annoyed by the price of bread--nothing was out-and-out bad, therefore 4 stars.

If you're looking for traditional French Canadian food, that's not really it. It feels like a European version of it. The menu doesn't really know what it wants to be about. That said, the food was good, but nothing special. Especially for the price! I know this is Kendall Square but still... SO overpriced! I flew in from NYC and found this gem of a restaurant thanks to a friend. The food is prepared perfectly, especially the duck. Simple yet flavorful tastes. Unique and memorable wines and ciders. Plus, friendly and attentive staff that make you feel at home in the cozy decor. Also, try the charcuterie. Yum.

Amazing food, great cocktails, and very friendly and knowledge staff. Try to arrive early and grab a drink at the small but unique bar. Only reason it didn't get five stars is because it was a little pricey and not that filling; I left kinda hungry.

Fabulous!  A good friend and I shared 3 excellent starters: the shrimp, the poutine, and the radishes and butter.  (The Poutine was my favorite of the three, with a gravy to die for!)  We followed this with the deer and blueberry entree, paired with the artichokes (lightly fried with a little fois gras).  Friendly and attentive service throughout.  Hidden gem is the beautiful little bar (seats 5) in the back room serving excellent cocktails!  Can't wait to go back.
